The authors urge policy makers in at-risk regions to consider if their heat action plans are sufficient for what might come. They also call for more research on how to communicate the uncertainty and risk of extreme heat events to the public and decision makers. (5/6)

The study also used climate models to project how the risk of record-breaking heatwaves will change in the future under different emission scenarios. They found that under a high-emission scenario, the probability of exceeding the current record will increase by 50% by 2100 (4/6)

However, they also found that in any region, there is a chance of having a much more extreme heatwave than ever experienced before. This is especially concerning for regions like Afghanistan and Central America, where the population is vulnerable due to limited resources. (3/6)

The study used extreme value statistics to estimate the probability of exceeding the observed daily maximum temperature record in 173 regions globally. They found that in 31% of regions, the current record is exceptional, meaning that it is unlikely to be broken soon. (2/6)
